&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; I encountered some problems due to URI length limits imposed by Web servers, even though the HTTP protocol does not set any limits on GET request length.
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; The easiest solution is to expose the resource using POST instead of GET but this violates REST principles, and the semantics of POST (I am using POST when I mean GET).
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; The other alternative is to divide the interaction in 2 steps:
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; 1 - POST my-algorithm/args x1=1&x2=2....
&gt;&gt;     This creates a resource that represents the algorithm&#39;s arguments we want to pass:
&gt;&gt;     201 Created
&gt;&gt;     location: /my-algorithm/args/args-resource-1
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; 2 - GET /my-algorithm/args/args-resource-1
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; This solution seems to be more RESTful but I fear it will complicate the interaction and potentially break statelessness (how long should the server keep the arguments just posted?).
&gt;&gt; I am really tempted to follow the first solution even though it violates REST principles because I don&#39;t see any drawbacks and it simplifies interaction.
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; I would appreciate some comments and suggestions.
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Thank you.
